The paper deals with filtering and estimation of sets of trajectories, which is a common problem in robotics (cs.RO) and computer vision (cs.CV). The use of probability hypothesis density filters is also relevant to control systems (cs.SY) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also proposes computationally efficient implementations, which could be of interest to the machine learning community (cs.LG).
